          %h3 Apple Trees
          %p For the past several months I have been making paintings of an apple tree in the backyard.  I work from life; that is, I stand in front of the tree and look at it, and the tree informs the decisions I make on canvas.
          %p The tree seems to me like an event, a spectacle.  The overall impact of the spectacle is the confluence of many factors:  the whirling gesture of the branches, towering overhead, sweeping forward and down in front, tangled and sagging under the weight of swelling apples; the rushing slope of the ground; being outside in the Georgia summer; the sky a white haze glaring through dark leaves; the ground cracking from drought; the shade at the base of the tree made luminous purple from the heat; sunlight on leaves like an amber syrup.
          %p Oddly, the spectacle of the tree, the all-at-once sensation, where everything about the scene seems to fall into its proper place, tends to clarify and deepen after a long period of looking.  This is why I work from one source repeatedly, on many surfaces over many months.  Over time a structure, like a blueprint, becomes embedded in my mind.  The paintings are all of a piece, all different stops on the way to one assertion, one statement about this particular tree.
          %p To isolate individual elements of the source, while required to some degree in the temporal construction of a painting, can mean denying the overall impact.  So I try to find  a way of working that feels true to being in the tree’s presence.  It means forgetting everything I thought I knew about how to paint (how to depict), and often seems to work against literal description.  Often it means working across the whole surface, tracing a course with my brush which echoes the path of my eyes.  Or sometimes it means painting without looking directly at the canvas, with the idea of getting at how the scene feels, in a tactile sense.  The goal is to move beyond mere description to arrive at an evocation.  To evoke a presence in paint.
