          %h3 Thesis Statement (Excerpt)
          %p Painting is an assertion of self.  As the self’s relation to the world is subject to change from one moment and one context to the next, so should painting be subject to change.  Painting is a reflection of life.  A life is a sum of decisions and a by-product of opposing forces.  Painting is an attempted union of oppositions.
          %p I have always had a very strong need for solitude and a need to distance myself from my context.  Painting sets up a triangular relationship between my self, the world and the canvas.  The painting then becomes a record of my confrontation with the world.  I work from observation and am concerned with the act of perceiving.  Perception is an active, fluid, mutable, often transient phenomenon.  There are innumerable ways to perceive a scene, and I employ different modes at different times in a painting.  At times I might rapidly shake head and eyes, like a cat about to pounce, in order to gauge an object’s spatial position from many subtle shifts in points of view.  Or I might try to fixate on a single central point, in which case the scene frequently disintegrates into a color patterning that seems to deny a spatial reading.  To see entails seeing differences; nothing is seen except in relation to something else.
          %p When I first got to Indiana I was tormented over what to depict, and even why to make depictions at all.  I was seized by a strong reductive impulse, where I wanted to pare everything down to something true, something personal, something about my looking.  I have always had a diaristic bent to the work—a desire to record the visual facts of my life.  The most immediate and obvious subject matter at this point was the studio.  Over time the studio came to represent different things, both sanctuary and battleground.  I see it now in the paintings as primarily a projection of the mind.
          %p I’ve since broadened my scope by painting Bloomington cityscapes from a rooftop downtown.  I have also broken with the dogma of working directly from the source, and am painting from pencil drawings and memory.  Initially I wanted to inject the whole experience of being on the roof into one large painting.  The impulse was toward expansion as opposed to the earlier reduction.  I’ve become aware of the investment I’ve made, and of the questions:  can a representational painting carry the weight of ideas that I desire, and can it be believable?
          %p I aspire to make a painting so clearly about looking that it is also about the looker; that it becomes a representation of both perceiver and perceived.  The panorama incorporates different points of view that I often try to link by working from peripheral vision:  measuring and depicting one area while focusing on a central point.  The idea is that the scene will be realized more truthfully, the way a faint star is seen only by looking off to its side.  In periods of frustration I use an intuitive mark - a mark simply informed by a gut reaction to the scene – all over the surface, dismantling the image, with the hope that the result will be more believable:  less of a facile depiction and more about the way the scene feels.  Sometimes I fear I’ll be left with no image at all, or with no significant, informed correlation to perception.  I desire a continual building toward completion, but it is always a tenuous building, involving constant failure.
          %p While I have no creed for how paint is applied, i.e. thick or thin, transparent or opaque, I do believe it necessary to assert the material, so that marks of paint are charged with a tension between representation and abstraction.  I suppose this is a way of acknowledging the impossibility of the endeavor:  that in the end one is always left with just a painting – a trace – rather than the scene, or the seen, or the vision – itself.  I want the surface of a painting to be a unified fabric of interwoven marks through which one can peer into the history of the process.  Painting, like life, is a struggle.  The process and technique of painting I have arrived at will, I hope, provide a record of the struggle.
          %p I would like the end of a painting to be like the beginning:  full of potential, ready for change, ready for a new record of a new insight.  But resolution very often occurs somewhere in the middle of the time spent on a painting.  At that point I may become aware of what the painting is about, and I begin to paint with resolve.  I may have had one idea at the outset, but now the painting has become about something different.  Perhaps I need to recognize this moment as the defining moment of the painting and leave it alone.  Often I end up effecting cosmetic changes to clarify the idea, leading to frustration and more destruction.  The way a painting looks is a result of myriad decisions made at different times, in different states of mind.  Some are good decisions, others not so good.  But one must accept those decisions and respond to what the painting needs.  Ideally, resolution would entail a balance between determination and abandon, stasis and movement, solace and turmoil.
