          %h3 Statement
          %p I am a representational painter working in oil.  At this time I am working at home from scenes that I look at every day:  The bathroom, the buildings outside the window, the studio, my head.  Subject matter is of lesser importance to me; the true subject of each painting is the looking itself.
          %p Though I began painting in high school it was not until the end of college that painting came to dominate my academic pursuits.  A year after graduating in English and theater I decided I was not cut out for the acting profession, and I relished the opportunity to take a year that The School of the Art Institute of Chicago.  There I decided to work from the model, and I struggled with two major challenges to painting from observation.
          %p The first challenge was to measure. On the first day of a figure class the instructor suggested that I try to paint the figure the same size as I saw it.  I was astonished to realize that I had never tried to do this before, and amazed at how difficult such a simple proposition would prove.  Suddenly scale and accurate measurement were crucial.  I was encouraged not to render the figure, but to see the figure in the space of a particular room, and to match the scale of the painting with that of my vision.
          %p The second challenge was how to use color.  I had always prided myself on my bold handling of color.  Using juxtapositions of bright, saturated color I tended to schematize the lights and darks of a painting.  But the colors I used were more or less arbitrary, rarely mixed beyond the secondaries, and were based more on a quick sensation that on sustained observation.  So, for a whole semester’s class at SAIC, I used a limited palette of black, white, yellow ochre and oxide red.  I now put much more effort into mixing colors to find differences.
          %p A consequence of facing these challenges is that now each painting requires a great deal more time.  In fact I never finish a painting so much as try to resolve it.  Even up to the last moment of the last session the painting must be susceptible to change—to a new record of a new observation.  The “completed” piece should, therefore, have a constant readiness; a constant coming-into-being.  One should not just see what is there; one should look for what could be there next.
